<module status="bronze">
  <h>an</h>
  <p><g>an</g>
    <en>in(side), within</en> is the (non-leniting) inessive <a href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions"
      >preposition</a>.</p>
  <p>The inessive preposition should not be confused with other uses of the particle <a
      href="?gd=an"><g>an</g></a>.</p>
  <section>
    <h>forms</h>
    <section id="indefinite">
      <h>indefinite</h>
      <p>The default form of the inessive preposition is the reduplicated <g>ann an</g> – <ul>
          <li><m>ann an</m> taigh <en>in a house</en></li>
          <li><m>ann an</m> aislingean <en>in dreams</en></li>
          <li><m>ann an</m> Nirribhidh <en>in Norway</en></li>
          <li><m>ann an</m> trì làithean <en>in three days</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>When the immediately following word begins with a labial consonant (ie. <g>b-</g>,
          <g>p-</g>, <g>m-</g>, <g>f-</g>) the (assimilated, co-articulated) form <g>ann am</g> is
        used instead – <ul>
          <li><m>ann am</m> bròig <en>in a shoe</en></li>
          <li><m>ann am</m> Pàrlamaid na h-Alba <en>in the Scottish Parliament</en></li>
          <li><m>ann am</m> Machair Aonghais <en>in Angus</en></li>
          <li><m>ann am</m> fichead latha <en>in twenty days</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that the non-reduplicated form <g>an</g> (or <g>am</g> before labials) is sometimes
        found as well.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="definite">
      <h>definite</h>
      <p>When the immediately following word is a form of the definite article, the linking form
          <g>anns</g> is used – <ul>
          <li><m>anns an</m> taigh <en>in the house</en></li>
          <li><m>anns a’</m> bhaile <en>in the town</en></li>
          <li><m>anns na h-</m>aislingean <en>in the dreams</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <!--<p><ed>Add note on ‘anns a-màireach’, ‘anns a h-uile ...’, ‘anns a bheil ...’</ed></p>-->
      <p>Note the following commonly used, fused forms – <ul>
          <li><m>san</m> taigh <en>in the house</en> ≈ <g>anns an</g> taigh</li>
          <li><m>sa</m> bhaile <en>in the town</en> ≈ <g>anns a’</g> bhaile</li>
          <li><m>sna h-</m>aislingean <en>in the dreams</en> ≈ <g>anns na h-</g>aislingean</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note also that these fused forms are occasionally found in older texts with an initial
        apostrophe – <g>’san taigh</g>, <g>’sa bhaile</g>, ...</p>
      <p>It is common to use fused forms when the immediately following word is a <a
          href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a> – <ul>
          <li><m>’nam</m> thaigh <en>in my house</en> ≈ <g>ann am mo</g> thaigh</li>
          <li><m>’nad</m> bhaile <en>in your town</en> ≈ <g>ann an do</g> bhaile</li>
          <li><m>’na h-</m>òran <en>in her song</en> ≈ <g>ann an a h-</g>òran</li>
          <li><m>’na</m> chraoibh <en>in his tree</en> ≈ <g>ann an a</g> chraoibh</li>
          <li><m>’nar n-</m>achadh <en>in our field</en> ≈ <g>ann an ar n-</g>achadh</li>
          <li><m>’nur</m> leapannan <en>in your beds</en> ≈ <g>ann am bhur</g> leapannan</li>
          <li><m>’nan</m> taighean <en>in their houses</en> ≈ <g>ann an an</g> taighean</li>
          <li><m>’nam</m> baile <en>in their town</en> ≈ <g>ann an am</g> baile</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that the fused forms are usually written without the initial apostrophe nowadays,
        which can lead to confusion with forms of the definite article.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="pronouns">
      <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
      <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>ann am mi</bad>, <bad>ann an t(h)u</bad>,
        ... , <bad>ann an iad</bad> – <ul>
          <li><m>annam</m>
            <en>in me</en></li>
          <li><m>annad</m>
            <en>in you</en></li>
          <li><m>innte</m>
            <en>in her/it</en></li>
          <li><m>ann</m>
            <en>in him/it</en></li>
          <li><m>annainn</m>
            <en>in us</en></li>
          <li><m>annaibh</m>
            <en>in you</en></li>
          <li><m>annta</m>
            <en>in them</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>ann am mise</bad>, <bad>ann an t(h)usa</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>ann an iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>annamsa</m>
            <en>in <emph>me</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>annadsa</m>
            <en>in <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>inntese</m>
            <en>in <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>annsan</m>
            <en>in <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>annainne</m>
            <en>in <emph>us</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>annaibhse</m>
            <en>in <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>anntasan</m>
            <en>in <emph>them</emph></en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>ann am mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>ann an t(h)u
          fhèin</bad>, ... , <bad>ann an iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>annam fhìn</m>
            <en>in myself</en></li>
          <li><m>annad fhèin</m>
            <en>in yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>innte fhèin</m>
            <en>in herself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>ann fhèin</m>
            <en>in himself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>annainn fhìn</m>
            <en>in ourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>annaibh fhèin</m>
            <en>in yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>annta fhèin</m>
            <en>in themselves</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>dependents</h>
    <section id="deps-comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <p>Like all (true) prepositions, <g>an</g> governs a noun complement in the dative case.</p>
      <p>These complements can belong to a number of different semantic classes.</p>
      <section id="deps-comp-human">
        <h>humans</h>
      </section>



      <p>Some examples – <ul>
          <li><g>ann am <a href="?gd=bogsa">bogsa</a></g>
            <en>in a box</en></li>
          <li><g>ann an <a href="?gd=càr">càr</a></g>
            <en>in a car</en></li>
          <li><g>ann an <a href="?gd=làmh">làimh</a></g>
            <en>in someone’s hand</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <module id="countries">
        <h>with names of countries</h>
        <h lang="gd">...</h>
        <p>Biblical examples – <xl id="basic-exs">
            <li>
              <gd>A Nis is iad so ainmeanna chloinn Israeil, a thàinig do’n Eiphit; thàinig gach
                duine agus a theaghlach maille re Iacob: Reuben, Simeon, Lebhi, agus Iudah, [...]
                Agus na h-anman uile a thàinig a mach a leasraidh Iacoib, bu deich agus tri fichead
                anam iad; oir bha Ioseph <m>’san Eiphit</m> a cheana. [...]</gd>
              <tr>Now these are the names of the children of Israel, which came into Egypt; every
                man and his household came with Jacob. Reuben, Simeon, Levi, and Judah, [...] And
                all the souls that came out of the loins of Jacob were seventy souls: for Joseph was
                in Egypt already. [...] [KJV]</tr>
              <ref text="160">Ecsodus I.1–5</ref>
            </li>
          </xl>
        </p>

      </module>

      <module id="towns">
        <h>with names of towns and cities</h>
        <p>Examples from Gairm – <xl id="gairm">
            <li>
              <gd>Ma rannsaicheas sinn air ais fada gu leòir chì sinn nach robh sgoilean <m>anns an
                  Oban</m> gus an ochdamh linn deug. Bha an sgoil bheag a b’ fhaisge air anns a’
                Chill Mhóir cóig mìle air falbh, agus tha e coltach gu robh an sgoil sin air an
                fheadhainn bu shine an Earra-Ghaidheal.</gd>
              <tr>If we research back long enough we will see that there were no schools in Oban
                until the eighteenth century. The closest little school was in Kilmore five miles
                away, and it appears that that school was one of the oldest in Argyll.</tr>
              <ref text="400-20">td. 363</ref>
            </li>
          </xl>
        </p>
      </module>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>uses</h>
    <section id="uses-comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <p><g>an</g> can be used to introduce the complement of certain verbs – <ul>
          <li><g><a href="?gd=tilg">tilg</a> ann an</g>
            <en>throw something into something</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
    <section id="uses-mod">
      <h>modifier</h>
      <p><g>an</g> can be used to introduce a modifier of a noun – <ul>
          <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="an-older-pedag">
              <li>
                <gd>Tha mo mhàthair a’ sgrìobhadh litreach gu m’athair a tha air falbh. Thubhairt mo
                  mhàthair, “An téid thu do bhocsa nan litrichean leis an litir seo, Iain?” “Théid,”
                  ars Iain, “falbhaidh mi an dràsda”. “Fuirich gus an dùin mi i is gus an cuir mi
                  seòladh oirre. Ceannaich fhéin stamp agus cuir oirre i.” Tha Iain a’ ruith sìos an
                  rathad leis <m>an litir ’na làimh</m>. </gd>
                <tr>My mother is writing a letter to my father who is away. My mother said, “Will
                  you go to the postbox with this letter, John?” “Yes, I will,” said John, “I will
                  leave now.” “Wait until I seal it and put an address on it. Buy a stamp and put it
                  on it.” John is running down the road with the letter in his hand. </tr>
                <ref text="621">td. 5</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Or a modifier of a verb – <ul>
          <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="an-verb-older-pedag">
              <li>
                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is <m>thug</m> an athair leis Iain agus Anna <m>anns
                    a’ chàr</m>. [...]</gd>
                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father took John and Ann in the car.
                  [...]</tr>
                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

    </section>
  </section>

