  <h id="aspectual"><i>an(n)</i> as an aspectual preposition</h>
  <p>Consider the following example –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><m><u>Bha</u> Raghnall <u>na shuidhe</u> fon a’ chraoibh</m>
      <en>Ronald was sitting/sat under the tree</en>, literally <en>Ronald was <u>in his sitting</u>
        ...</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Here, the prepositional form <strong>na</strong> (= <strong>ann an a</strong>
    <en>in his</en>) serves as the predicate of the verb <strong>bha</strong>
    <en>was</en>, and the incorporated personal determiner (‘possessive adjective’)
      <strong>a</strong>
    <en>his</en> agrees with the subject of <strong>bha</strong>, ie. <strong>Raghnall</strong>
    <en>Ronald</en>, cf. <m>bha <u>Ealasaid</u>
      <u>na</u> suidhe</m>
    <en>Elizabeth was sitting/sat</en>, <m>bha <u>sibh</u>
      <u>nur</u> suidhe</m>
    <en>you were sitting/sat</en> &amp;c. The complement of the preposition is the verbal noun
      <strong>suidhe</strong>
    <en>sitting</en>, derived from the inchoative/perfective (‘change of state’) verb
      <strong>suidh</strong>
    <en>sit (down), become seated</en>. Thus, while <m>shuidh Raghnall</m>
    <en>Ronald sat (down)</en> describes an event, the sentence <m>bha Raghnall na shuidhe</m>
    describes the state resulting from such an event – <en>Ronald is in the state of having sat
      down</en>.</p>
  <p>This idiom can be used with the following inchoative verbs –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>suidh</strong>
      <en>sit (down)</en>, eg. <m>shuidh e</m>
      <en>he sat (down)</en>, <m>bha e na shuidhe</m>
      <en>he was sitting/seated/sedentary</en>
      <ulx id="suidh">
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha ise <m>’na suidhe</m> air a’ bhruaich is a cùl ris, is a casan rùisgte anns a’
            bhùrn fhuar, is i a’ plubadaich leotha air a socair.</gd>
          <tr>She was sitting on the bank with her back to him, and her bare feet in the cold water,
            and splashing with them leisurely.</tr>
          <ref text="40">td. 69</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha sinn <m>’nar suidhe</m> air balla ìosal mu choinneamh Tigh Dhréimisdail [...]</gd>
          <tr>We were sitting on a low wall in front of Drimsdale House [...]</tr>
          <ref text="36">td. 32</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha iad uile <m>’nan suidhe</m> aig am biadh, an triùir aca. Sheas a h-athair ’s
            thubhairt e [...]</gd>
          <tr>They were all sitting at [their] dinner, the three of them. Her father stood up and he
            said [...]</tr>
          <ref text="198">td. 31</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd> Bha mi <m>nam shuidhe</m> air bruaich uaine ri taobh cidhe beag.</gd>
          <tr>I was sitting on a green bank beside a little quay.</tr>
          <ref text="2">td. 44</ref>
