          <gd>A bheil thu nad chadal fhathast? Chan eil. ’S ann a tha mi <m>nam dhùisg</m>.</gd>
          <tr>Are you asleep still/yet? No. I am awake.</tr>
          <ref text="607">td. 276</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha i <m>na leth-dhùsgadh</m>.</gd>
          <tr>She was half-awake.</tr>
          <ref text="605">td. 161</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha i <m>na làn dhùisg</m> a-nise.</gd>
          <tr>She was fully awake now.</tr>
          <ref text="601">td. 251</ref>
        </lix>
      </ulx>
    </li>
    <li><strong>stad</strong>
      <en>stop, come to a halt</en>, eg. <m>stad i</m>
      <en>she stopped</en>, <m>bha i na stad</m>
      <en>she was stopped/stationary/at a standstill</en>
      <ulx id="stad">
        <lix>
          <gd>Cha robh i fada <m>’na stad</m> nuair a dh’fhairich i bhith ’ga togail suas ’san
            athar.</gd>
          <tr>She had not been stooped for long when she felt herself being lifted up into the
            air.</tr>
          <ref text="294">td. 27</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Tha a’ chùis <m>na stad</m>.</gd>
          <tr>The affair/matter/business is at a standstill.</tr>
          <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
        </lix>
        <lix>
          <gd>Bha na càraichean <m>nan stad</m> fad uair a thìde.</gd>
          <tr>The cars were stopped/stationary for an hour.</tr>
          <ref text="608">td. 120</ref>
        </lix>
      </ulx>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>Predicates like <strong>na[m] shuidhe</strong> can occur in a few other verbal
    constructions – <ulx id="xx_na_vn">
      <lix>
        <gd>Dh’èirich e <m>na sheasamh</m>.</gd>
        <tr>He stood up.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 509</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Dh’èirich e <m>na shuidhe</m>.</gd>
        <tr>He sat up.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 556</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Leum e <m>na sheasamh</m>.</gd>
        <tr>He leapt to his feet.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 509</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Chuir iad an crann <m>na sheasamh</m>.</gd>
        <tr>They stepped the mast.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 509</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>cuir cuideigin <m>na shuidhe</m>.</gd>
        <tr>seat someone, sit someone down</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 358</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Fhuair mi Francis <m>’na dhùisg</m>, agus bha e anabarrach toilichte m’ fhaicinn.</gd>
        <tr>I found Francis awake, and he was very happy to see me.</tr>
        <ref text="81-9-18">td. 2</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>’Nuair bha i tighinn faisg air an fhearann, chunnaic i duine <m>’na shuidhe</m> air
          carraig am beul an làin, agus stiùir i direach air.</gd>
        <tr>When she was coming close to the land, she saw a man sitting on a rock in front of the
          tide[?], and she steered straight for him.</tr>
        <ref text="199">td. 298</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Thug mi sùil os mo chionn ach gu dé an nì a bha ’gam chumail <m>’nam stad</m>.</gd>
        <tr>I looked up but what thing was keeping me stationary.</tr>
        <ref text="400-11">td. 273</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Mus sealladh tu riut fhèin rinn iad as aig peilear am beatha, a’ fàgail a’ chàir <m>na
            stad</m> far an robh e.</gd>
        <tr>Before you would look at yourself (?), they ran for their lives, leaving the car stopped
          where it was</tr>
        <ref text="309">td. 8</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Chuir e a ghunna <m>’na laighe</m> air an talamh [...]</gd>
        <tr>He laid his gun on the ground [...]</tr>
        <ref text="204">td. 36</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Dh’éirich an saighdear <m>’na sheasamh</m> air an ùrlar.</gd>
        <tr>The soldier stood up on the floor.</tr>
        <ref text="217-1">td. 111</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Chaidh athair <m>’na stad</m> mar uaireadair a’ dol a bhualadh.</gd>
        <tr>His father stopped like a clock that was going to strike.</tr>
        <ref text="204">td. 44</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>They can also appear as noun modifiers – <ulx id="n_mod">
      <lix>
        <gd>figear <m>na laighe</m></gd>
        <tr>a reclining/recumbant figure</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 238</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>Note that these six inchoative verbs can also occur with the usual imperfective
    particle <a href="?gd=ag">ag</a>, but with a progressive or habitual reading, rather than a
    resultative one –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><m>Bha Raghnall <u>a’ suidhe</u> fon a’ chraoibh</m>
      <en>Ronald was in the process of sitting (himself) down under the tree; Ronald used to sit
        (down) under the tree</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Examples – <ulx id="ag">
      <lix>
        <gd>Tha a’ ghaoth <m>a’ laighe</m> a-nis.</gd>
        <tr>The wind’s subsiding now.</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 238</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>“Cha tèid mi ann,” ars esan, is e <m>a’ suidhe</m> sìos a-rithist.</gd>
        <tr>“I shan’t go,” he said, sitting down again.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 556</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Tha mi <m>a’ suidhe</m> – tha mi a’ gluasad gu bith a’ cur mo thòin sa chathair.</gd>
        <tr>I am sitting down – I am moving to be putting my buttocks on the chair.</tr>
        <ref text="607">td. 276</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Tha seo <m>a’ dùsgadh</m> cuimhne air ...</gd>
        <tr>This awakens memories of ...</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 251</ref>
        <note>transitive usage in this example</note>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>Note also that other inchoative verbs cannot occur in this construction – <bad>tha
      Seumas na bhàsachadh</bad> and <bad>tha mi nam thuiteam</bad> are unacceptable for <en>James
      is dead</en> or <en>I have fallen</en>. <ed>Contrast with other resultative constructions eg.
      glaiste, air a ghlasadh? cf. Cox p. 276: Bha mi dùisgte. An robh thu dùisgte? (Islay,
      Argyll).</ed></p>
  <hh>bi na[m] chadal</hh>
  <p>Although <strong>caidil</strong>
    <en>sleep</en> is not an inchoative verb (but rather an imperfective/activity verb), it is used
    in this construction as well, eg.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><m>Tha Dòmhnall <u>na chadal</u></m>
      <en>Donald is asleep</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Examples – <ulx id="na_cadal">
      <lix>
        <gd>Ach ged a bha mo shuilean duinte, cha robh mi <m>’nam chadal</m> idir [...]</gd>
        <tr>But though my eyes were closed, I was not at all asleep [...]</tr>
        <ref text="232-1">td. 67</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha Ailig <m>na chadal</m> air an t-sòfa, a bhroinn làn uisge-beatha, agus am botal ’s
          a’ ghlainne air bòrd beag ri thaobh.</gd>
        <tr>Alec was asleep on the sofa, his belly full of whisky, and the bottle and the glass on a
          little table beside him.</tr>
        <ref text="2">td. 110</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha mi <m>nam chadal</m> anns a’ chathair</gd>
        <tr>I was sleeping in the chair</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 107</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>A bheil thu <m>nad chadal</m> fhathast? Chan eil. ’S ann a tha mi nam dhùisg.</gd>
        <tr>Are you still asleep? No, I am awake.</tr>
        <ref text="607">td. 276</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>Other constructions – <ulx id="cadal_other">
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha e eadar <m>a chadal</m> ’s a dhùisg.</gd>
        <tr>He was between sleeping and waking.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 106</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>An neach nach cinn <m>na chadal</m>, cha chinn e na dhùisg.</gd>
        <tr>He who will not prosper in his sleep, will not prosper when awake.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 106</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bhitheadh e a’ coiseachd <m>na chadal</m>.</gd>
        <tr>He used to walk in his sleep.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 106</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Dh’fhàg e <m>’na chadal</m> e trì mìle bho’n uaimh.</gd>
        <tr>He left him asleep three miles from the cave.</tr>
        <ref text="205">td. 71</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Ghrad thuit thu <m>nad chadal</m> [...]</gd>
        <tr>Suddenly you fell asleep [...]</tr>
        <ref text="81-10-24">td. 182</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>The default imperfective <strong>a’ cadal</strong> is usually used with habitual
    meaning – <ulx id="ag_cadal">
      <lix>
        <gd>Aon oidhche chuir e dà dhuine gu taigh an Deucoin airson Rob a phronnadh, ach nuair a
          bhris iad a-steach bha leabaidh Roib falamh. Bha e air a bhith <m>a’ cadal</m> ann an
          taigh nàbaidh bho dh’innis Mab dha an cunnart san robh e.</gd>
        <tr>One night he sent two men to the Deacon’s house to rough up Rob, but when they broke in
          Rob’s bed was empty. He had been sleeping at a neighbour’s house since Mab told him the
          danger he was in.</tr>
        <ref text="2">td. 115</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <hh>bi na[m] ruith</hh>
  <p>The manner-of-motion (activity) verb <strong>ruith</strong>
    <en>run</en> is also often used in this construction, eg.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><m>Bha sinn <u>nar ruith</u></m>
      <en>we were running</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Examples – <ulx id="na_ruith">
      <lix>
        <gd>Tha i <m>na ruith</m>.</gd>
        <tr>She is running.</tr>
        <ref text="609">td. 51</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha a’ chlann <m>nan ruith</m> anns a’ phàirc.</gd>
        <tr>The children were running in the park.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 39</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>Other constructions – <ulx id="na_ruith_other">
      <lix>
        <gd>Dh’fhalbh iad <m>nan ruith</m>.</gd>
        <tr>They went away at a run.</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 313</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd><m>nan dian-ruith</m>.</gd>
        <tr>at full tilt, hell for leather</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 313</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Chunnaic mi sibh <m>nur ruith</m>.</gd>
        <tr>I saw you running.</tr>
        <ref text="607">td. 325</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>The default imperfective <strong>a’ ruith</strong> is used with a direct object and
    in idiomatic usages – <ulx id="ag_ruith">
      <lix>
        <gd>Chan eil an trèana / an t-uisge <m>a’ ruith</m>.</gd>
        <tr>The train’s / the water’s not running.</tr>
        <ref text="605">td. 313</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>ann a bhith <m>a’ ruith</m> a’ Mhòid</gd>
        <tr>in running the Mod</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 494</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha an cù glè dhèidheil air a bhith <m>ruith</m> clach.</gd>
        <tr>The dog was very fond of chasing stones.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 494</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha sinn <m>a’ ruith</m> leis a’ ghaoith.</gd>
        <tr>We were running before the wind.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 495</ref>
        <note>a sailing idiom</note>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
  <p>cf. <strong>bha i na coiseachd</strong>
    <en>she was walking</en> [2017 Richard Cox <i>Geàrr-Ghràmar na Gàidhlig</i> td. 276].</p>
  <hh>bi na[m] chrùbadh/chrùban</hh>
  <p><en>be crouched</en> – <ulx id="na_chruba">
      <lix>
        <gd>bha e <m>na chrùban</m> ri taobh na h-uinneig</gd>
        <tr>he was crouched beside the window</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 183</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Choimhead e air an dithis a bha <m>nan crùban</m> mun teine.</gd>
        <tr>He looked at the pair who were crouched around the fire.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 183</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>rach <m>nad chrùban</m></gd>
        <tr>crouch</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 183</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Chaidh e <m>na chrùban</m> ri a thaobh.</gd>
        <tr>He crouched down beside him.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 183</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha iad <m>nan leth chrùban</m>.</gd>
        <tr>They were half crouching.</tr>
        <ref text="601">td. 183</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha e <m>na chrùbadh</m>.</gd>
        <tr>He was crouched.</tr>
        <ref text="607">td. 276</ref>
      </lix>
      <lix>
        <gd>Bha mi <m>nam chrùban</m>.</gd>
        <tr>I was crouched.</tr>
        <ref text="607">td. 325</ref>
      </lix>
    </ulx>
  </p>
